  <static seed="1457" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations55.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {-\frac{4}{y}+\frac{5}{y-3}} = 1 }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{6,-2\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of fractions, we multiply each term in this equation by the common denominator, which is <m>{y\mathopen{}\left(y-3\right)}</m> in this example.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp {-\frac{4}{y}+\frac{5}{y-3}} = 1 \\
   \amp {-\frac{4}{y}y\mathopen{}\left(y-3\right)+\frac{5}{y-3}y\mathopen{}\left(y-3\right)} ={y\mathopen{}\left(y-3\right)} \\
   \amp {-4\mathopen{}\left(y-3\right)+5y} = {y^{2}-3y} \\
   \amp {-4y+12+5y} = {y^{2}-3y} \\
   \amp {y+12} = {y^{2}-3y} \\
   \amp {y+12-y^{2}+3y} = 0 \\
   \amp {-y^{2}+4y+12} = 0 \\
   \amp -({y^{2}-4y-12})=0 \\
   \amp -({y+2})({y-6})=0 \\
   \amp {y+2}=0 \:\: or\:\: {y-6}=0 \\
   \amp y={-2} \:\: or\:\: y={6}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p><alert>Checking</alert></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp y = 0 \amp \;\amp  y - 3=0 \\
   \amp y=0 \amp \;\amp  y=3
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must exclude <m>0</m> and <m>3</m> from the solution set. There is no conflict with those two solutions we got, so the final solution is <m>y={-2}</m> and <m>y={6}</m>.</p>
</solution>
